column1: 153043;instagram;2018-12-13 04:50:00;TRUE;;"reposted from @thefatsextherapist sexual boundary violations are sexual trauma [image text] *content warning on sexual trauma talk*
this is the reframe i offered during the pleasure principle talk last week that got the biggest woah reaction from the audience and even folks who came up to talk with me afterwords
shift away from thinking about sexual assault as one narrow experience. and what i mean by that is assuming it‚Äôs only penetrative
column3: and only happening to a person with a vagina
column4: w aggressive violence or threats of violence or weapons - (this is too narrow a definition)

column1: thinking of only one narrow understanding of sexual violence erases the many things that i would consider sexual trauma. as a sexual assault counselor
column2: i often reframe any sexual boundary violation as a a form of sexual violence. and violence doesn‚Äôt mean there has to be threat of harm or a weapon involved. but any act of someone not checking in with you and picking up on your verbal and non verbal cues can contribute to an experience that didn‚Äôt feel good before
column4: or after. this includes romantic nonsexual interactions

column1: the purpose of reframing this understanding of sexual violence is to realize that we may be carrying around sexual trauma and not realize it. we may be reenacting our sexual trauma. we may be reacting to others based off this unprocessed sexual trauma
column2: bc we haven‚Äôt acknowledged it. many of us have experienced something akin to a boundary violation and im here to tell you that counts as trauma

column1: anytime someone removed a condom and didn‚Äôt tell you
column2: that‚Äôs a boundary violation. anytime someone coerced or pressured you into saying yes. anytime someone uses substances to induce your yes

column1: now i‚Äôm not offering this reframe to suggest you report to police. you get to decide how you feel about your trauma. trauma is relative. what i find traumatic might not feel the same to someone else& that doesn‚Äôt cancel out our experiences. you get to decide

column1: 153074;instagram;2018-12-13 05:24:20;FALSE;"i guess i have to address this. content warning for mentions of sexual abuse.
if you've been following me for a while
column2: you undoubtedly at some point saw me promote comic writer eric m. esquivel's fantasmagoria and border town series. with their use of horror and latin american folklore
column3: they seemed to be the perfect fit around here
column4: hence my video reviews and the fact that i went quite out of my way to go to a comic book signing and even planned on going to another (now cancelled) one this weekend. if you follow comics news
column5: you've probably heard about the abuse allegations against esquivel by a former co-worker from his time working at a comic book store in tucson
column8: was pretty horrifying and brought back a lot of memories of my own experience in an emotionally and sexually abusive relationship. worse yet
column9: both her post and responses from others since also confirmed she was not the only victim and he may have even pursued underage girls. the illustrator and colorist on border town recently confirmed that they were not aware of the extent of his wrongdoings
column10: though it sounds as if the higher ups at dc comics were
column11: which doesn't do much for the accusations of misogyny in the company.

column3: i do not plan on removing my video reviews of fantasmagoria and border town. doing so  would seem like i was trying to hide the fact that i had enjoyed them
column5: at the time i definitely did. that being said
column6: i do not think i will be able to continue reading these series if they continue or reread the previously released issues without them being tainted. border town especially dealt with fear and power dynamics in society
column7: something that someone who misused those things should not be discussing in a meaningful way outside of a therapist's office on the subject of ""how do i not do this again?"" the fact that the main characters are all teenagers
column8: two of the main four being girls

column1: 153115;instagram;2018-12-13 06:16:27;FALSE;"there‚Äôs so so so much i love about this picture

1. i just snapped it real quick after my rock purchase to show my partner my new rock necklace i got. i was beaming. the smile was genuine. i felt so warm inside. sharing my happiness with someone i am absolutely in love with!

2. my best friend who i‚Äôm visiting here in san diego did my make-up for the day (which i never do for myself) and i had a cute outfit on and i felt cute all day we got to go to a beautiful lookout and then this place called old town where we had great mexican food and i got rocks!

3. i finally realised how much progress i‚Äôve made in the past year. i may be late to comment about #metoo but we all have our own timeline of healing. and so much we each feel comfortable with sharing. just under a year ago everything i knew about my life was flipped upside down. i went to therapy. i went to police officers. i reported and testified and it was the hardest thing i‚Äôve ever done in my life. back in late april
column2: i had a huge breakdown because of it
column4: i ran. hid out with my friends in detroit for a while. didn‚Äôt know my next move
column5: didn‚Äôt believe my life was worth a next move. but then
column6: i moved to lexington. i started doing yoga
column8: and focused more on loving myself and the people around me. focused more on love
column10: the love others had shown me was all i had left. that‚Äôs why i do these things
column11: because they were my way out of the most difficult time of my life. i set intentions. i meditated. i worked so hard with myself. i am still working. there are still bad days. and there always will be. but right now i am here. i am happy. and grateful. and i feel love again. for myself. and the people i hold close to my heart.";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;felicia.rey;FŒûlicia RŒûy ‚Ä¢a small bean‚Ä¢;;0;False;15;0;0;145;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/00f5158b03bb539a442f2181e393c44a/5D141D20/t51.2885-15/e35/46289421_428606554341936_2482696880168288664_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"there‚Äôs so so so much i love about this picture

column1: ‚Ä¢we all have a wound. it‚Äôs what makes up human. this archetypal wound is represented by chiron.

column1: ‚Ä¢ something i‚Äôve been thinking about is how to walk the line between privacy and authenticity on social media. i value privacy
column2: but i also believe that reclaiming yourself after a wounding experience is so powerful. no
column3: my story isn‚Äôt like so many women bravely shared within the #metoo movement. but why should my experience be stigmatized? when i believe that

column6: it tends to trigger past memories of endured stress. ptsd. i think that‚Äôs what they call it. but i have other names for it: resiliency
column8: patience. i amaze myself by how far i‚Äôve come since. i am grateful... and i have so many stories that have not been told...

column1: 153627;instagram;2018-12-13 19:03:13;FALSE;"ever since i watched @brenebrown amazing ted talk i fell in love with the entire ted institution. when i moved back to uganda in jan 2018 i put ted on my vision board. i had no idea how i would get there
column2: or what i would even talk about. i just knew that i wanted to be a part of the global community of like minded people who wished to inspire and be inspired by others.

column1: when i got the call that i was invited to be a speaker at a ted event i couldn't believe it. that i was chosen out of so many and so early on in my career with my organisation being so young. i was and still am amazed that i ticked off this item on my bucket list so early and easily.
i will forever be grateful to the amazing people who helped me get here.
so i raise a toast to my first (hopefully many more to come) ted talk and a toast to never giving up on yourself. cheers ‚ù§
on the 7th of december 2018 our founder ameena babirye was one of the speakers at the tedxnaguru event.
the event was about female empowerment
column2: gender equality and gender based violence.

column30: or what i would even talk about. i just knew that i wanted to be a part of the global community of like minded people who wished to inspire and be inspired by others.

column1: when i got the call that i was invited to be a speaker at a ted event i couldn't believe it. that i was chosen out of so many and so early on in my career with my organisation being so young. i was and still am amazed that i ticked off this item on my bucket list so early and easily.
i will forever be grateful to the amazing people who helped me get here.
so i raise a toast to my first (hopefully many more to come) ted talk and a toast to never giving up on yourself. cheers ‚ù§

column1: at times it is important for me to read a book that burst‚Äôs my convenient bubble and give me a harsh wake up call to the realities of the world that we live in today. issues of child abuse and sexual trafficking are unfortunately a very real issue yet sometimes we become oblivious to the suffering others have to endure. it isn‚Äôt because we are not compassionate but our own lives take over and we somehow ‚Äòforget.‚Äô until a book like ‚Äògirl trafficked‚Äô is recommended to me and i lose sleep for a few nights whilst i read it.
an autobiography based on the true story of a young girl called zoe who suffered the most horrific form of abuse first by a mother who should have loved her and then a system
column2: which ultimately failed her. but despite the horrific ordeal she suffered she had the courage and the strength to break through the shackles of years of emotional and physical torment and make a better life for herself. ‚Äògirl trafficked‚Äô is a book of hope yet i felt anger whilst reading it. i felt angry with her family and especially her mother. i felt anger at the professionals whose care she was under and who had a responsibility to respond to her pleas of help and finally i felt anger at the vile individuals who trafficked and abused her.

column4: no welfare and still they have everything in the world they want and need.... i am so proud of them being such smart and beautiful young ladies. my girls have reached out to so many people outside of california just to be disappointed. in spite of it all they are still happy and excelling in school like never before...if you haven't noticed they are being raised by a strong mom. i have my days healing from domestic violence. healing from the trauma of it all.. from the grief and healing from being a battered woman and hiding it. but everyday i am their mom
